# Juana Julia Guzmán, an example of struggle

Author: Revolución Obrera

Time: 2023-03-02T08:00:00-05:00

Images: ['[Juana-julia.png](https://www.revolucionobrera.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Juana-julia.png)']

Tags: ['8 de marzo 2023', 'día internacional de la mujer', 'Emancipación de la Mujer', 'femininismo', 'Juana Julia Guzman', 'Movimiento Femenino Revolucionario']

Categories: ['Emancipación de la mujer', 'Efemérides']

<!--METADATA-->

* Updated 2023-03-01

[![Juana Julia Guzmán, example of fighting1](Images/Revolucion Obrera/2023-03-02T08-00-00-05-00/Juana-julia.png)](https://www.revolucionobrera.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Juana-julia.png)** Photography by Juana Julia Guzmán. Source: Orlando False Archive, Banco de la República. **

Juana Julia Guzmán, was a historic leader of the peasant and femenine movement of the first half of the twentieth century. He was born in Corozal, Sucre in 1892 in the sinus of a humble peasant family of Afro and indigenous origin. Because of the sugar of poverty, he could not attend school, so he began to work from a very young age in the classification of tobacco leaves in the business that his godfather Cristóbal Badel had, which exported tobacco to Germany. Alquebrar the business of his godfather following the first imperialist war, Guzmán moved to Montería in 1916, where he worked as an unmarried employee and worker. It is there that it came into contact with the Italian socialist Vicente Adamo, who was exiled in the country.

With the ideological influence of the Italian socialist, both found the society of artisans and workers of Córdoba in 1918 and take up -earth recovery actions in the Loma Grande region, being there constitute the basterojo of Loma Grande in order to fight for the earth and defend The rights of peasants, settlers and agricultural workers. Subsequently, "red bastions" in Callejas and Canaltete are created.

In 1919, Juana Julia Guzmán would found the Lamujer's Redemption Society, of which she would be president. Most of the women who integrated this movement were workers or peasants. This was one of the pioneer organizations to organize the women of the popular masses parallel to their rights in the midst of a macho society and quite behind as of the department of Córdoba of that time.

Among other organization initiatives in which Juana Julia participated, the creation of the Socialist Hospital, the Obrera School, popular library, and some cooperatives that were called "anonymous commercial societies" participate. All these were institutions created in order to deem and dignify the lives of workers and women in the field.In the early 50s, due to the reactionary war that was developed in the field and the threats against him he moved from the sinú region to Montería. In the 70s, with the National La Asociation Foundation of Peasant Users(Anuca), Juana Julia is linked to this organization where she transmits all their knowledge to their new fighting companies and guides them in the practice of the recoveries. In addition, she was one of the drivers of the creation of the Women's Committee of the ANUC. In 1975, he died in the Granada neighborhood, Montería.

We remind the great Juana Julia Guzmán, as one of these Colombian women who dedicated their lives to the struggle of their class and their people against the dominant Las Classes. It is an example of struggle for the new popular deluchas generations, which must keep in mind that, despite living under capitalist and macho, it is always necessary to fight, because as Juana Julia himself repeated: ** “The coward does not make history does not make history ”**.

News Source: [https://www.revolucionobrera.com/mujer/juana-julia/](https://www.revolucionobrera.com/mujer/juana-julia/)

