# In a penny reduces Avá -Canoeiro area - The New Democracy

Author: Rosana Bond

Description: The Tocantins Avá-Canoiro tribe was celebrating the legalization of its territory a few weeks ago, last November/December, when it was surprised

Publish Time: 2023-03-02T12:00:00-03:00

Modified Time: None

Updated Time: None

Images: ['[ava_canoeiro_6-fa7-768x546-1.jpg](https://anovademocracia.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/ava_canoeiro_6-fa7-768x546-1.jpg)']

Section: Povos Indígenas

Tags: ['Avá-canoeiro']

Type: article

<!--METADATA-->

![](Images/A Nova Democracia/2023-03-02T12-00-00-03-00/ava_canoeiro_6-fa7-768x546-1.jpg)Photo: Reproduction

The Tocantins Avá-Canoiro Tribe was celebrating the legalization of itsterritory a few weeks ago, last November/December, when it was formed by an absurd decision of federal judge Eduardo de Assis Ribeirofilho.

He took a third from Ti Taego ãwa, leaving the Indians with only pieces(where most can not plant)and cutting access to the waters of the Javaés River. According to Eliane Franco, from the Indigenous Member Council(SME)-Regional Goiás/Tocantins, the Avá-Canoiro people resorted to judicial of declaration embargoes.

##### ** Discarded the expertise **

“The judge did not take into account the expertise that was held, declaring an indigenous Landing Taego ãwa as the traditional land of the Avá-Caneiro people. There were a failure in the judge's decision in the case(…), among them the decrease indigenous, access to the Javaés River and the permanence of nonindigenic occupants within the territory, ”he explains.

"The Avá-Canoeiro did not accept any kind of negotiation," she said. "Approved presented is disadvantageous to us indigenous people, considering that they have a uninhabitable place for the people," noted one of the tribal leaders, Kamutaja Silva ãwa.]

The court decision misrepresented studies for indigenous deterritory demarcation, already guaranteed in articles 231 and 232 of the 1988 Constitution.

