# Protest against Herrera Law, launched by workers

Author: Philippine Revolution Web Central

Publish Time: 2023-03-02T99:00:00-04:00

Modified Time: None

Description: Workers have protested earlier at the Commission on Human Rights in Quezon City to assert the dismissal of the anti-worker Herrera Law in conjunction with its 34th anniversary. According to the M movement

Images: ['[workers-protest-herrera-law-may-day-multimedia-photo-1024x683.jpg](https://philippinerevolution.nu/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/workers-protest-herrera-law-may-day-multimedia-photo-1024x683.jpg)']

Categories: ['Workers']

Type: article

<!--METADATA-->

![](Images/Philippine Revolution Web Central/2023-03-02T99-00-00-04-00/workers-protest-herrera-law-may-day-multimedia-photo-1024x683.jpg )Workers earlier protested at the Commission on Human Rights in Quezoncity to assert the dismissal of the anti-worker Herrera Law at the same time as its 34th anniversary. According to the May Uno movement(SME), the legal law has made the contractualization that eradicated the work security of workers.

Herrera Law was enacted on March 2, 1989 under the Coryaquino regime. It was named after its main pusher Sen. Ernestoherrera. Herrera is a former chairman of the Leading Trade Union Congress ofthe Philippines.

According to the KMU, the law authorities are authoritative to police and military to resort to strikes and prevent them through Assumption of Jurisdiction(AJ), against the rights of workers.

"Through the AJ, implementing strikes, the requirements were tightened to launch a strike, and the police and military were allowed to break strikes and unions in the workshop," KMU said.

It further explained, "although the law forbid labor-only contracting, eased other forms of contractualization. In essence, it eases the ability of capitalists to receive contractual that wage benefits. "

For workers and unions, Herrera Law is a huge "nightmare" today. "The contractualization is still widespread throughout the country maintaining a wages and lack of benefits. It also intensifies the rights of workers to union, strike, strike, and declare," KMU said.

In the Philippines, it is estimated that about 9.4 million Filipinos remain contractual workers according to Bird Foundation data in 2018.

News Source: [https://philippinerevolution.nu/angbayan/protesta-kontra-herrera-law-inilunsad-ng-mga-manggagawa/](https://philippinerevolution.nu/angbayan/protesta-kontra-herrera-law-inilunsad-ng-mga-manggagawa/)

